04483nmm a2200637Ia 9781501707902DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)992508154  a97815017079027 a10.7591/97815017079022doi  a(DE-B1597)483641  a(OCoLC)957057046  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDK908.85b.C36 201704a958.45/072231 aCampbell, Ian W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKnowledge and the Ends of Empire :bKazak Intermediaries and Russian Rule on the Steppe, 1731-1917 /cIan W. Campbell. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Knowledge and the Ends of Empire, Ian W. Campbell investigates the connections between knowledge production and policy formation on the Kazak steppes of the Russian Empire. Hoping to better govern the region, tsarist officials were desperate to obtain reliable information about an unfamiliar environment and population. This thirst for knowledge created opportunities for Kazak intermediaries to represent themselves and their landscape to the tsarist state. Because tsarist officials were uncertain of what the steppe was, and disagreed on what could be made of it, Kazaks were able to be part of these debates, at times influencing the policies that were pursued.Drawing on archival materials from Russia and Kazakhstan and a wide range of nineteenth-century periodicals in Russian and Kazak, Campbell tells a story that highlights the contingencies of and opportunities for cooperation with imperial rule. Kazak intermediaries were at first able to put forward their own idiosyncratic views on whether the steppe was to be Muslim or secular, whether it should be a center of stock-raising or of agriculture, and the extent to which local institutions needed to give way to imperial institutions. It was when the tsarist state was most confident in its knowledge of the steppe that it committed its gravest errors by alienating Kazak intermediaries and placing unbearable stresses on pastoral nomads. From the 1890s on, when the dominant visions in St. Petersburg were of large-scale peasant colonization of the steppe and its transformation into a hearth of sedentary agriculture, the same local knowledge that Kazaks had used to negotiate tsarist rule was transformed into a language of resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History.  aKazakh Steppe, Kazak intermediaries, Kazakh figures, Kazakh political culture, Soviet Union, Russian colonialism.  aRussian imperial rule, late-imperial Russian colonial rule.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2017z9783110547764oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170790240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501707902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501707902/original  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2017  aZDB-23-DGGb2017